<!-- Begin Title -->
<h1>Inverse Hyperbolic Functions</h1>
<!-- End Title -->
<hr class=3D"margin-t-1-8 margin-b-3-4">
<!-- Begin Total Content -->
<!-- Begin Content -->
<div class=3D"entry-content">
<p>
The inverse hyperbolic functions, sometimes also called the area hyperbolic=
 functions (Spanier and Oldham 1987, p.&nbsp;263) are the <a href=3D"https:=
//mathworld.wolfram.com/MultivaluedFunction.html">multivalued
 function</a> that are the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Inverse=
Function.html">inverse functions</a> of
 the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/HyperbolicFunctions.html">hyp=
erbolic functions</a>. They are denoted
 <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/InverseHyperbol=
icFunctions/Inline1.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;m=
ax-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"60" height=3D"21" alt=3D"cosh^(-1)z">,
 <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/InverseHyperbol=
icFunctions/Inline2.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;m=
ax-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"58" height=3D"21" alt=3D"coth^(-1)z">,
 <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/InverseHyperbol=
icFunctions/Inline3.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;m=
ax-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"59" height=3D"21" alt=3D"csch^(-1)z">,
 <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/InverseHyperbol=
icFunctions/Inline4.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;m=
ax-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"59" height=3D"21" alt=3D"sech^(-1)z">,
 <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/InverseHyperbol=
icFunctions/Inline5.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;m=
ax-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"57" height=3D"21" alt=3D"sinh^(-1)z">,
 and <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/InverseHype=
rbolicFunctions/Inline6.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:10=
0%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"58" height=3D"21" alt=3D"tanh^(-1)=
z">.
 Variants of these notations beginning with a capital letter are commonly u=
sed to
 denote their <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/PrincipalValue.html"=
>principal values</a> (e.g., Harris and
 Stocker 1998, p.&nbsp;263).
</p>
<p>
These functions are <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/MultivaluedFun=
ction.html">multivalued</a>, and hence require <a href=3D"https://mathworld=
.wolfram.com/BranchCut.html">branch cuts</a> in the <a href=3D"https://math=
world.wolfram.com/ComplexPlane.html">complex
 plane</a>. Differing branch cut conventions are possible, but those adopte=
d in this
 work follow those used by the <a href=3D"http://www.wolfram.com/language/"=
>Wolfram
 Language</a>, summarized below.
</p>
